               their emergence as analog quantum simulators. Here, we explore
               this phenomenon in an atomically thin layer of semiconductor
               MoSe\_{2}, which we embedded in a heterostructure enabling charge
               tunability. Shining an intense pump laser with a small detuning
               from the material resonances, we generate a large population of
               virtual collective excitations and achieve a regime where
               interactions with this background population are the leading
               contribution to the ac Stark shift. Using this technique we study
               how itinerant charges modify-and dramatically enhance-the
               interactions between optical excitations. In particular, our
               experiments show that the interaction between attractive polarons
               could be more than an order of magnitude stronger than those
               between bare excitons.",
