  pages     = "813--822",
  abstract  = "The radiation at the boundary of an isotropic or cubic medium by
               a polarization at 2ω, the amplitude of which is proportional to
               the product of the incident laser field at ω and a spatial
               derivative of this field, is examined theoretically. A complete
               expression for the intensity and polarization of the reflected
               harmonic radiation as a function of the angle of incidence and
               state of polarization of the incident laser beam is derived. The
               angular dependences are in good agreement with observations on
               Si, Ge, and Ag. Some additional experimental results, not
               previously reported, are described. The magnitude of the
               nonlinearity due to bound electrons in these cubic materials is
               related to the square of the linear susceptibility, and agrees
